ature yet dared to be ready to steal the initiative of combat. A samurai always lived three feet from death and no one knew this like a veteran such as Masahiro.", "link_list": [], "image_list": [], "html": "The banner lord pulled hard on the reins of his horse and came to a halt, bringing the entire entourage to a stop behind him as the ogre bounded towards their ranks. With a snap Masahiro produced a large signaling fan and immediately the ranks of the Hosokawa began to ready their bows and spears. It was only by the grace of Kojuro's recognition that one hundred men did not loose arrow and spear into the monster. With quiet appraisal the samurai watched the exchange as Wuppo and Rena were unmolested amidst their reunion. Masahiro wrapped his left hand around the reins of his horse and maneuvered it towards Kojuro. His face was impassive, like a stone monument in its stoic indifference, as he regarded the spectacle. As his eyes looked between Wuppo and Kojuro, and then finally Rena, he leveled his war fan at Kojuro."}, "post-70060": {"user": "Wuppo", "user_num": 2387, "timestamp": "1498831996000", "message": "Wuppo, with very few exceptions, had spent nearly every interaction he'd ever had with humans while they'd had\u00a0bows, spears, swords, and every other conceivable weapon - sharp and blunt - leveled at him. It was only after Wuppo had placed Kojuro back on to his horse that he looked to see the stern-faced\u00a0Masahiro, menacing him with a.. fan?\"HAAAHHH HUH-HUH-HUH-HUH!!\" the ogre's low, loud, booming, guffaw sounded out again, and then slowly turned to a gravely chortle at Masahiro's demand for answers at the point of a fan. Wuppo obviously knew very little of human culture, but surely, he surmised, they didn't arm even their least capable warriors with the same implements the ogre had observed the daintiest of human females carrying on hot days. There was no way Tawakoshi had changed that much in his absence.Wuppo looked at Rena as he gave Kojuro a st